Feb 23
Inspired by the ICT Silver Bullet methodology as publicly discussed by Kyle Ng (JadeCapFX), this strategy provides an educational, rule-based implementation of liquidity sweep and Fair Value Gap (FVG) concepts for TradingView users.

This script is designed to demonstrate how time-based liquidity and price displacement ideas can be structured into a systematic trading framework. It is not affiliated with or endorsed by ICT, Michael Huddleston, Kyle Ng, or JadeCapFX.

CORE METHODOLOGY
This strategy is based on commonly taught ICT concepts that focus on liquidity behavior and price displacement, rather than traditional indicators.

Key ideas implemented in this script include:

Liquidity Pools: Prior session highs and lows (Asian, London, and New York reference levels) are used as potential areas where liquidity may reside.
Liquidity Sweeps: Trades are only considered after price has taken one or more of these reference highs or lows.
Fair Value Gaps (FVGs): A three-candle price pattern is used to approximate displacement and identify potential execution zones.
Time-Based Execution: Trades are restricted to specific intraday windows to align with periods of increased market activity.

The goal is to participate in directional moves after liquidity has been engaged, rather than attempting to predict market direction.

TRADE SETUPS & EXECUTION LOGIC
Liquidity Conditions
Asian session high / low
London session high / low
9 AM New York candle high / low
At least one of these levels must be swept before a trade can be taken.

Execution Windows
AM Window: 10:00 – 11:00 (New York time)
PM Window: 14:00 – 15:00 (New York time)
Only the first valid Fair Value Gap appearing during an active window is eligible.

Directional Rules
Bearish FVGs require a prior high sweep
Bullish FVGs require a prior low sweep

Trade Management
Entry: Limit order at the Fair Value Gap
Stop Loss: Behind Candle 1 of the FVG
Take Profit: Fixed Risk-to-Reward multiple (default 2R)
One trade per execution window
Optional forced close at 4 PM New York time

KEY FEATURES
Automated plotting of Asian and London session ranges
Liquidity sweep detection across multiple reference levels
Fair Value Gap identification using a three-candle model
Configurable AM and PM execution windows
Fixed risk-to-reward trade management
Optional end-of-day position closure
Clear visual markers for ranges, execution windows, and FVG zones

IMPORTANT NOTES
Not True Order Flow
This strategy does not use bid/ask or tick-by-tick order flow data. Liquidity sweeps and Fair Value Gaps are approximated using standard OHLC price data available on TradingView.

Performance Sensitivity
Strategy results are highly sensitive to:
instrument selection
timeframe
volatility conditions
commission, fees, and slippage assumptions
execution quality
Users should configure realistic trading costs in the Strategy Properties tab before evaluating results.

Market Dependence
Performance may vary significantly across different markets (indices, commodities, crypto) and across different timeframes. Time-based execution windows are evaluated using the America/New_York timezone.

EDUCATIONAL DISCLAIMER
This script is provided for educational and research purposes only. It is not financial advice. Past performance does not guarantee future results.

Users are solely responsible for their own testing, risk management, and trading decisions. Always forward-test thoroughly on a paper or simulated account before considering live trading.
Mar 2
Release Notes
VERSION 2.0 UPDATE

This version includes the following improvements:
- Added price label display on all key levels (Asian, London, 9AM ranges)
- Added customizable colors for better chart organization
- Enhanced FVG box visualization with better color options
- All original trading logic and strategy conditions remain unchanged

The core strategy functionality is identical to version 1.0. This update only improves the visual presentation and makes the script more customizable.

HOW TO USE
Go to the script settings and look for "Color Settings" to customize the colors for Asian high/low, London high/low, 9AM high/low, and FVG signals.

You can also toggle "Show Price Labels" to display or hide the price values on the key levels.
